subSection.paragraph:
The critical molecular feature determining the specific, active uptake of agrocin 84 and agrocinopines via agrocinopine transporters appears to be a sugar 2-phosphate (
El Sahili et al., 2015
; 
Li et al., 2019
; 
Zhang et al., 2020
). An additional reason for publishing the structure of agrocinopine C at this time is that recent papers (
Li et al., 2019
; 
Matveeva and Otten, 2021
; 
Zhang et al., 2020
) have cited and presented incorrect structures for this molecule based on the previous synthesis of an incorrect version (
Lindberg and Oscarson, 1993
). It was apparent that Tate for some time considered that the compound D-glucos-2-yl sucros-2-yl phosphate, synthesised by 
Lindberg and Oscarson (1993)
, was the correct structure for agrocinopine C as per Tate’ s correspondence with Lindberg and Norberg in 1990 and later with 
Dessaux et al. (1998)
. However, it is now clear that the original structure determined by Savage and Tate (
Savage 1983
) was correct and modern NMR spectroscopic methods have confirmed this.

Lindberg and co-workers made two attempts at synthesising agrocinopine C: D-glucos-2-yl sucros-6-yl phosphate and D-glucos-2-yl sucros-2-yl phosphate (
Lindberg et al., 1992
; 
Lindberg and Oscarson, 1993
). Their attempted synthesis of D-glucos-2-yl sucros-6-yl phosphate (
Lindberg et al., 1992
) should have yielded a product identical to agrocinopine C, but a phosphate coupling (
2
Jpoc
4.6 Hz) to a carbon at 95.8 ppm indicates that coupling was to carbon 1 rather than carbon 2. Furthermore, acid degradation of this synthetic product yielded glucose-1-phosphate which is consistent with synthesis of D-glucos-1-yl sucros-6-yl phosphate. The synthetic compound (
Lindberg et al., 1992
) was biologically active, but this does not unequivocally prove identity with the structure of the natural product agrocinopine C, rather that a particular feature of the molecule required for uptake recognition has sufficient similarity to the natural product. A subsequent paper describing a revised synthesis of agrocinopine C, in this case referred to as “agrocinopin C” (
Lindberg and Oscarson, 1993
), has a sucros-2-yl phosphate linkage which is in error. Although Tate clearly considered for some time that the structure of the 
Lindberg and Oscarson (1993)
synthetic product was correct, it is important that the structure of the natural compound is now corrected, as several recent publications that either refer to or are based on 
Lindberg and Oscarson (1993)
have the incorrect linkage of the sucrosyl moiety for the structure of agrocinopines C and D (
Li et al., 2019
; 
Matveeva and Otten, 2021
; 
Zhang et al., 2020
).

From a structural perspective, it is of interest to consider which part of the agrocinopine molecules might be recognized by the related periplasmic binding proteins (
Kim and Farrand, 1997
) that mediate their uptake, and also for the uptake of agrocin 84, as distinct from the quite different (P–O and P–N) phosphoryl-cleavage sites required to release the sucrose as an essential nutrient in the case of the agrocinopines C and A. The latter process also releases the biologically active mono-nucleotide (
Murphy et al., 1981
), later referred to as the “Toxic Moiety, TM84” (
El Sahili et al., 2015
) from agrocin 84, which is required for the antibiosis against 

Agrobacterium

pathogens carrying a suitable Ti plasmid. Recent studies (
Li et al., 2019
; 
Zhang et al., 2020
) have shown that sugar phosphate analogues with the appropriate 2-phosphate substitution can also be taken up via the transport mechanism encoded by the 
acc
operon. Thus it appears that it is the sugar-2-phosphate motif, where the sugar is either D-glucose (agrocinopine C) or L-arabinose (agrocinopine A), that is recognized by the uptake mechanisms coded by the 
accA
genes on the respective Ti-plasmids. The hexose-2-P motif is also mimicked by agrocin 84, allowing this “Trojan horse” molecule to be actively taken up, followed by intracellular hydrolysis to 
form the
toxic “TM 84” (
El Sahili et al., 2015
) which acts as an inhibitor of leucyl-tRNA synthetase (
Chopra et al., 2013
).

In solutions of D-glucose (the hexose associated with agrocinopine C), essentially only pyranose anomers are observed, with a small amount of β- furanose (
Angyal and Pickles, 1972
; 
Angyal, 1991
) and a very small amount (0.002%) of the aldehyde (
Williams and Allerhand, 1977
). However, phosphorylation at the adjacent 2-hydroxyl position markedly changes these ratios in agrocinopine C such that the glucose-2-phosphate moiety shows a considerable amount of the two furanosyl anomers (α- 6%, β- 8%) in addition to a large increase in the intermediate acyclic aldehyde and/or aldehyde hydrate isomer (10%) (
Table 2
, 
Table S1
). Similarly, in aqueous solution of L-arabinose, the sugar associated with agrocinopine A, a mixture of anomers with only a small amount of the open ring form (0.03%) was observed (
Hayward and Angyal, 1977
), however phosphorylation in the 2-hydroxy position greatly increased the concentration of acyclic aldehyde and/or aldehyde hydrate isomer (8%) (
Table 2
, 
Table S1
).

High voltage paper electrophoresis (HVPE) was carried out according to the method of 
Tate (1981)
using Orange G, fructose, 2-deoxyadenosine and inorganic phosphate as markers. Relative mobilityvalues were estimated using the mobility of either Orange G (
RmOG
), or 2, 4-dinitrobenzene sulfonate (
RmDNBS
) with fructose as the non-migrating marker (
RmOG
0.0) except in the borate buffer where 2-deoxyadenosine was used as the non-migrating marker. In the pH range used, Orange G has formal charge 2 and 2,4-dinitrobenzene sulfonate has formal charge 1. The buffers used were 0.75 M formic acid/1.0 M acetic acid (pH 1.7) and 0.2 M ammonium borate buffer (pH 9.2). The voltage used for paper strips (15 × 
55 cm
) was 
2000 V
for 0.5 h for both buffers.

UV absorbing species were detected on electrophoretograms using a UV lamp (
254 nm
, 
366 nm
). Non-UV absorbing products were detected by developing chromatograms in silver nitrate reagent for vicinal hydroxyl groups (
Trevelyan et al., 1950
). Phosphomolybdate reagent was used for detection of phosphate (
Harrap 1960
), 
p
-anisidine for hexoses and pentoses (
Hough et al., 1950
), and urea phosphoric acid reagent for ketoses (
Avela et al., 1977
).
